[normal]KPMG additional examples tranche 1 – [bold]Condition A[bold]              [bold]              [bold]              [bold]              [bold]       [bold] Appendix[bold]Example 1a: basic example[bold]A, B and C are members of ABC LLP.  A is allocated 2 points and B and C are each allocated 4 points.  Regardless of the level of profit A will receive 20%, while B and C will receive 40% each.  
[normal]All three members receive no disguised 
[normal]remuneration,
[normal] they each have a variable interest in the overall profits of the partnership.
[normal]Example 1b: ‘benchmark’ and variable amounts[bold]A, B and C award themselves ’salaries’ of £20,000, £40,000 and £40,000 respectiv
[normal]ely and agree that the total profit will be shared in proportion to those salaries.
[normal] If the overall profits of the partnership are more or less than £100,000 then each partner will share in the deficit or surplus in proportion to their agreed salary.  
[normal]This
[normal] arrangement is in substance identical to example 1a: each partner has an interest in the profits of the partnership which is variable by reference to the overall profits of the partnership.  It is not relevant that the partnership has chosen to describe t
[normal]his arrangement by reference to a salary.
[normal]Example 1c: guaranteed amounts[bold]Continuing example 1b, individual D joins the LLP.  He is also awarded a ‘salary’.  His total profit share will be calculated as a proportion of the total profits of ABC LLP in the sa
[normal]me way as A, B and C but in his first year he is guaranteed a total profit share of no less than £30,000.  If his allocated share of the profits is less than this it will be borne by the other members; D will receive his profit share in priority to A, B an
[normal]d C.
[normal]D’s guaranteed profit share of £30,000 is disguised salary as it is fixed.  Accordingly, unless it is reasonable to expect that ultimately D’s share for the period will exceed £37,500, such that his overall return is not substantially wholly fixed, he
[normal] will meet Condition A.
[normal]Example 1d: capped variable interests[bold]E joins the LLP described in 1b above. 
[normal]Like D, s
[normal]he is awarded a 
[normal]‘
[normal]salary
[normal]’
[normal]. Her total profit share will be calculated as a proportion of the total profits of ABC LLP in the same way as A, B and C 
[normal]but her total profit share cannot exceed £25,000.  
[normal]As E is sharing directly in the overall profits of the partnership up to a certain point and her profit share is not paid in priority to the other members she will not meet Condition A unless, in practice
[normal], the overall profits of the partnership are expected to be such that she will 
[normal]realistically 
[normal]always receive £25,000
[normal].  If this were so, it would imply that her total received was not in practice a variable share of total profit equal to her ‘salary’ as a fr
[normal]action of all salaries, but was simply a fixed sum meeting Condition A.
[normal]Example 1e: businesses with stable or reliable profits[bold]Same as example 1b above, but the profit forecast is reliable or the nature of the business is such that profits are not signific
[normal]antly variable from year to year such that it is unlikely that profits will be materially greater or less than £100,000.
[normal]The fact that the overall profits of the business may be accurately forecasted and/or are stable from year to year does not mean that C
[normal]ondition A is necessarily met: each of the partners has an interest in the partnership which will vary with the overall profits of the partnership, even if those overall profits are predictable or are not significantly variable.
[normal]Example 1[bold]f[bold]: timing differen[bold]ces between cash and profit[bold]Facts as 
[normal]1b above
[normal].
[normal] However
[normal], 
[normal]the ‘salaries’ are distributed in-year.  It is agreed that to the extent there are insufficient 
[normal]profits,
[normal] excess
[normal] drawings will only be 
[normal]satisfied 
[normal]out of future profits of the firm
[normal] (meaning the drawings 
[normal]in the following years would be less than the affected members’ profit allocations)
[normal]. 
[normal]The distribution to members of drawings representing advances against allocations 
[normal]of  profit
[normal] share does not of itself change the position from that in 1b.
[normal]Example 2: disc[bold]retionary awards[bold]Please see attached marked-up versions of Examples 1A and 14 from HMRC’s 10 December Guidance.
[normal]Example [bold]3a: sharing in divisional profits only[bold]AB LLP has four members 
[normal]A
[normal], B, C and D.  A and B work in division X and C and D work in division 
[normal]Y.  Division X generates profits of £10
[normal],000
[normal] and Y of £90
[normal],000
[normal].  
[normal]The LLP deed provides that
[normal] A and B will share the profits of division X and that C and D will share the profits of division Y.  
[normal]All four members meet condition A as none of them receive a shar
[normal]e of the overall profits of the firm.
[normal]Example [bold]3[bold]b[bold]: whole firm profits shared on discretionary basis between members of divisions (i)[bold]The facts are the same as example 
[normal]3
[normal]a except that 
[normal]the LLP deed provides that profit allocation is at the discretion of the 
[normal]members.  T
[normal]he four members 
[normal]meet and, as per their terms of reference, they consider a range of factors including the financial performance of each division, the need for the divisions to work together and support each other, and the overall strategic direc
[normal]tion of the firm. They 
[normal]agree
[normal] 
[normal]that A and B will share profits of £
[normal]15,000
[normal], leaving C and D to share £
[normal]85,000
[normal].
[normal]Assuming the members have properly exercised their discretion under terms of reference based on more than just divisional profit sharing, they will n
[normal]ot meet condition A as their profit shares are each partly dependent on the overall profits of the whole firm.
[normal]Example 3c: whole firm profits shared on discretionary basis between members of divisions (ii)[bold]The 
[normal]facts are the same as example 3b
[normal] except that
[normal] t
[normal]he 
[normal]four members agree
[normal] 
[normal]that A and B will share profits of £
[normal]1
[normal]0
[normal],000 while 
[normal]C and D 
[normal]will
[normal] share £
[normal]9
[normal]0
[normal],000
[normal].
[normal]The four members will not meet condition A as their profit shares are still partly dependent on the overall profits of the entire firm,
[normal] 
[normal]notwithstanding that 
[normal]the resulting shares are the same as if profits were shared on a purely divisional basis.
[normal]Example [bold]3d: part divisional, part pro-rata split[bold]The facts the same as above example 3a except that the four members agree in advance that half of each division’s pro
[normal]fits will be split between the partners in that division, and half will be pooled and split equally between all the partners. Using the example above, A and B are therefore allocated £17.50. C and D are allocated £32.50.
[normal]We see two possible interpretations
[normal] of the legislation, either:
[normal]The four members will now not meet condition A as their profit shares are partly dependent on the overall profits of the entire firm.
[normal]Or:
[normal]The firm’s total profit should be treated as two amounts.  The first, 
[normal]division
[normal]ally alloca
[normal]ted amount then meets Condition A while the second, 
[normal]equally split 
[normal]amount does not.  The relative proportions of the two amounts for a member will determine whether that member meets Condition A.
[normal]Example [bold]4[bold]a[bold]: bonus pool for high performers[bold]A is a member of 
[normal]XY LLP. A receives a fixed share of £90,000
[normal] the terms of which result in it being considered to be disguised salary
[normal]. XY sets aside a proportion of profits each year as a 
[normal]bonus pool to reward high performing members.  Whilst the 
[normal]overall 
[normal]pool will vary with 
[normal]profits, the 
[normal]share of that pool 
[normal]allocat
[normal]ed
[normal] to 
[normal]an 
[normal]individual member will depend on their individual personal performance.  All members are eligible to receive a share of this profit pool and A typically receives a bonus ranging from £25,000 to £35,000 each y
[normal]ear. 
[normal]A will 
[normal]not meet
[normal] condition A as less than 80% of her expected profit share is fixed.  
[normal]Example [bold]4[bold]b[bold]: infrequent bonuses[bold]The same conditions as in 3a but 
[normal]A
[normal] only occasionally receives a bonus allocation.
[normal]A will meet condition A as her expected profit shar
[normal]e is just her fixed share.
